  S → NT5 NT36

Each nonterminal in a Chomsky‐normal grammar (with no ε‐productions) derives at least one terminal, and whenever you expand by binary rules you add the lengths of the two children.  So any string derived by S has length

  |w| = |w₁| + |w₂|,

  |w| ≡ |w₁|+|w₂| mod 2.

Because every nonterminal must emit at least one terminal before terminating, |w₁| and |w₂| are both ≥1.  Hence the only way to get an odd total length (like 13) is for one of |w₁|,|w₂| to be even and the other odd.  

A quick inspection of their productions shows:

 • NT5 either goes to a pair of nonterminals or directly to a single terminal “t3” or “t7”.  
 • NT36 likewise either goes to two nonterminals or to one of “t4”, “t1” or “t6”.

– Similarly, every expansion of NT36 yields either two nonterminals each of which can only ever resolve to a single terminal (1+1=2) or one terminal (length 1).  

So both NT5 and NT36 can only produce lengths in {1,2}.  Therefore S can only produce lengths in {1+1,1+2,2+1,2+2} = {2,3,3,4}.  In particular, it cannot produce length 13.
